    {
        "content": "<p>Your type ascriptions don't do anything the way you've written them; <code>f (x : Y)</code> means \"parse <code>x : X</code> as a <code>Y</code>, then call <code>f</code> with the result\". But in your case this doesn't result in the type <code>Y</code> being recorded with <code>x</code>.</p>",
        "id": 473779545,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1727711750
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>f (by exact x : Y)</code> means \"elaborate <code>f (_ : Y)</code>, then fill the hole with <code>x</code> when you're done with <code>f</code>\"</p>",
        "id": 473779847,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1727711799
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Really though you should get around this by defining <code>def GroupCompletion.mk : GroupCompletion := Quotient.mk x</code> or similar</p>",
        "id": 473779957,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1727711824
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks, I was missing the elaboration order part, and I did not now about this <code>by exact</code> trick. I agree that the construction should be abstracted as a def anyway.</p>",
        "id": 473781333,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Carlier",
        "timestamp": 1727712163
    },
